var/Rules={"<html>
<body><font face="calibri">
<h1 id="Top">Rules</h1>
<h2>Universal</h2>
<ul>
<li>If the admin team perceives that you make the game more stressful for others, without providing any positive benefits, you will be removed.</li>
<li>With the consent of all players directly involved, any player interaction rules can be waived.</li>
<li>Do not seek out trouble.  Minding your own business is a solution to many petty issues.</li>
</ul>

<h2>OOC</h2>
<ul>
<li>Where possible, be kind.  If not kind, be chill.  Don't instigate.</li>
<li>You may ask an admin to provide reasoning for their decisions.  They are not required to answer you.</li>
<li>Do not willfully drive players from the game.  Assist new players.</li>
<li>No form of bug abusing is allowed. If you think itï¿½s a bug, chances are it is one.</li>
<li>In general, do not interact between your alts.  Admin permission to do so may be granted.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Roleplay/Game</h2>
<ul>
<li>Do not engage in erotic roleplay in such a way that it makes others uncomfortable.</li>
<li>Do not spill IC information over the OOC channel.</li>
<li>Responses to actions should generally refer in some way to said action; emotes full on fluff with only minor references or full-on omission should be avoided and might incur a warning from the staff in severe cases.</li>
<li>This is a roleplay game.  Do not take negative actions against AFK players.</li>
<li>The above is waived if a character goes AFK over the course of a combat scenario.  Take care of yourself.</li>
<li>If someone has to go AFK in a hostile situation, they will still be there ICly.  Please be courteous if this happens, but do not let it stymie your RP.</li>
<li>If you attempt to avoid character conflict by logging out when you know or believe you will lose, you will either accept the death/other consequences of losing the conflict or be banned for the remainder of the wipe.</li>
<li>If you attempt to avoid character conflict by stalling out the situation or calling for unnecessary admin arbitrage, you will either respond or be banned for the remainder of the wipe.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Combat</h2>
<ul>
<li>Combat requires at least two sides; the combat scene ends when members of all sides but one are down.</li>
<li>If you're downed but your opponent allows you to leave, you might leave the combat scenario.</li>
<li>If you choose/are forced by opponent to remain, you keep that RP mode on and await finalization of the combat scenario.</li>
<li>Any kind of event character faced down by multiple opponents has a right to invoke limits on the number of opponents they face at the time/choose the order of fights; similar rules can be invoked in normal fights by mutual player agreements.</li>
<li>No skills with the exception of: Meditation, Heal, Give Power, Send Energy can be utilized during countdown and using any of the latter is only allowed for participants in the combat scenario/automatically makes one a participant.</li>
<li>Meditation cannot be utilized in combat scenarios outside of countdowns.</li>
<li>In case of interruptions, the specific action being interrupted should be halted and wait for resolution of the interruption.</li>
<li>In case of interrupting pursuit of retreating characters (which did not/could not invoke their <b>free retreat</b>), getting the pursuing party below 50% of their health at the time of RP will be treated as success - this will work on a honor system unless you make us code it in.</li>
<li>To interrupt a result of combat, the interrupting party must've been present at the start of the combat or become part of the scene during the verb part.</li>
<li>Save attempts are considered an instance of interruption.</li>
<li>Exception: Dramatic Interruption - a person who wasn't part of the combat scenario is allowed to interfere, but they forsake <b>all retreat options</b> and they become the only party interfering.</li>
<li>Dramatic Interruptions can be denied by the person who'd be subject to the result of the scenario; normal interferences cannot but heed rules of courtesy and good writing for that.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Intents</h2>
<ul>
<li>Injury Intent is required for actions that end up temporarily affecting the character in a negative way: wounding, short imprisonment, capture.</li>
<li>Lethal Intent is required for actions that have the potential of permamently affecting the character in a negative way: killing, maiming, sealing, transmuting, indefinite imprisonment, involuntary augmentation.</li>
<li>If you're utilizing non-wooden swords, fire element attacks - you're automatically subjected to Injury Intent from your opponent.</li>
<li>If you're utilizing cursed attacks, poison, maiming attacks - you're automatically subjected to Lethal Intent from your opponent.</li>
<li>If you're declaring lethal intent you're <b>required</b> to use injury intent while fighting.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Retreat</h2>
<ul>
<li>Anyone is allowed a <b>free retreat</b> at any point in combat.</li>
<li>The above rules can only be invoked ONE time against any person/group you are facing. All future retreats against said person/group will have to either be allowed by them or result of interruption.</li>
<li><b>Free retreats</b> recover after era transitions.</li>
<li>Going into immediate pursuit after a party utilizing their <b>free retreat</b> is NOT allowed.</li>
<li>Returning to a combat scenario after retreating is NOT allowed.</li>
<li>Using means of enhancing your retreat like: invisibility, teleportation, power concealment does not lead to an automatic retreat, but it will modify the necessary interruption threshold to 75%.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Death</h2>
<ul>
<li>Killing without sufficient reason to end another player's story is highly discouraged and noted for future reference by the admin team.</li>
<li>Prior to any sort of battle/skirmish, you must have clearly stated OOCly that you have lethal intent towards the party of whom you wish to kill.</li>
<li>Ensure that you notify all participants of a fight if you have lethal intent active.</li>
<li>Everyone has one save attempt allowed for them, but can have more if the person who KO'd them allows it.  Exceptions ('hyper lethal') situations can be invoked by the admin team where no saves are allowed.</li>
<li>During 'hyper lethal' rules, any knockout performed can be followed by a kill at the end of scenario - even if the killing party would be ultimately downed at the end of the scenario.</li>
<li>During 'hyper lethal' rules, you are not allowed to not kill a party you knocked out nor pass off the kill to a third party.</li>
<li>In order for a differet person than the one who scored a KO to kill a player, the killer must have permission from the person who knocked the victim out and they need to fulfil the presence requirements for interruptions.</li>
<li>If save occurs, the kill decision right passes to the saving party; this regards non-lethal character interactions like looting or wounding as well.</li>
</ul>
</body>
</html>

